 to other legal means to safeguard what matters to them.To articulate their claims, Native peoples have resourcefully used the languages of cultural resources under environmental and historic preservation law; of sovereignty under treaty-based federal Indian law; and, increasingly, of Indigenous rights under international human rights law. Along the way, Native nations still draw on the rhetorical power of religious freedom to gain legislative and regulatory successes beyond the First Amendment.The story of Native American advocates and their struggle to protect their liberties, Defend the Sacred casts new light on discussions of religious freedom, cultural resource management, and the vitality of Indigenous religions today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFreedom of religionzUnited States. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aIndians of North AmericaxReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh  aAmerican Indian.  aAmerican Indians.  aArctic National Wildlife Refuge.  aBears Ears.  aDakota Access Pipeline.  aElizabeth Shakman Hurd.  aFinbarr Curtis.  aGreg Johnson.  aHobby Lobby.  aIndian religion.  aKeystone XL.  aNative American studies.  aNicholas Shrubsole.  aPeter Nabokov.  aSuzan Shawn Harjo.  aTodd Morman.  aUN DRIP.  aUS law.  aWinnifred Sullivan.  aburial grounds.  acultural resource management.  aeagle feathers.  alegal studies.  amedicine men.  apeyote.  aprotests.  apublic land management.  areligious ceremonies.  areligious observances.  areligious rituals.  areligious studies.  areservation.  awhale hunt.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-